DOP external-validation reference
=================================

dop_reference.csv holds dilution-of-precision (GDOP/PDOP/HDOP/VDOP/TDOP)
reference vectors for a range of satellite geometries, computed by an
independent third-party authority and used to externally validate Kshana's own
`orbit::dop` (see tests/dop_reference.rs). These files are not part of the
Kshana source and are not shipped in the published crates/packages — they exist
only for the test suite.

Oracle
------
gnss_lib_py 1.0.4 — the Stanford NAV Lab GNSS library (open source, Apache-2.0;
peer-reviewed in JOSS, 2023: D. Knowles, A. Kanhere, B. Triplet, G. Gao,
"gnss_lib_py: Analyze GNSS Data with Python"). DOP is a deterministic function
of line-of-sight geometry alone, so matching gnss_lib_py's numeric output for a
fully-specified geometry is a genuine *external* cross-check of Kshana's design-
matrix assembly, 4x4 inversion and ENU projection — exactly as the reference
frames are validated against IAU SOFA/ERFA. It is independent of Kshana (a
different language and code path) and authoritative.

Provenance / reproducibility
----------------------------
Generated by the committed generate_dop_reference.py (run with gnss_lib_py
1.0.4 under Python 3.11). Each emitted row was additionally cross-checked
against an independent numpy `(GᵀG)⁻¹` computation (max relative difference
< 1e-9). The ENU line-of-sight convention is [cos el·sin az, cos el·cos az,
sin el], matching Kshana's orbit::enu_basis / orbit::dop, so the geometries are
identical by construction and all five DOP factors agree to machine precision.

Format
------
dop_reference.csv: '#'-prefixed comment lines, then one row per geometry:
  label ; n ; el_deg(|-separated) ; az_deg(|-separated) ; GDOP;PDOP;HDOP;VDOP;TDOP
The geometries span well-spread (PDOP ≈ 2), minimal 4-satellite, and
pathological (near-coplanar / all-high-elevation, DOP in the hundreds) cases so
the test exercises the vertical/horizontal projection, not just benign geometry.
